-- South African Stocks Advance For First Day in Four, Led by Anglo Platinum
-- Garth Theunissen
-- 2010-09-20T15:25:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/south-african-stocks-snap-three-day-drop-led-by-anglo-platinum-investec.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  increased for the first time in four days, rising
297.37, or 1.1 percent, to 28,710.93 at the close in
Johannesburg.  
 The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s largest producer
of the metal, added 7.70 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 681.20 rand.
Platinum demand will outpace supply in 2012-2015, after being
balanced in 2011, Macquarie Bank said in a report.  
 Wesizwe Platinum Ltd.  (WEZ SJ), the explorer of the
precious metal, rose 6 cents, or 3.9 percent, to 1.62 rand, the
steepest rise since Sept. 8. Platinum rose to a four-month high,
gaining 0.8 percent to $1,633.25 an ounce.  
 Investec Plc  (INL SJ), a private bank and wealth manager,
rose the most in a week, rallying 1.60 rand, or 2.9 percent, to
56.87 rand, snapping two days of decreases. The lender plans to
securitize 250 million pounds ($391 million) of mortgages and
has found investors who are keen to take up the issue, the
Financial Times reported today, citing people familiar with the
company that it didn’t identify.  
 Naspers Ltd.  (NPN SJ), Africa’s largest media company,
increased 5.24 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 312.98 rand, the biggest
advance in a week. The owner of Internet shopping companies
bought a controlling stake in Multiply.com, a social shopping
website, for an undisclosed amount.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, climbed 6.20 rand, or 2 percent, to 311 rand.
Oil rose for the first time in five days, rallying as much as
1.9 percent to $75.07 a barrel.  
